[9] <a href="javascript:card_browser(242)">Summit of Amon Hen</a> <br>
<br>
Free Peoples (39 + 3)<br>
Possessions :<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(180)">Hobbit Sword</a> x 2<br>
Frying Pan x 2<br>
Mithril Coat x 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(194)">Sting</a> x 2<br>
Bill the Pony x 2<br>
Events :<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(179)">Hobbit Stealth</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(178)">Hobbit Intuition</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(190)">Power According to His Stature</a> x 4<br>
Seek and Hide x 2<br>
Conditions :<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(1011)">Nice Imitation</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(314)">Fear</a>ing the Worst x 2<br>
O Elbereth! Githoniel! x 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(196)">A Talent for Not Being Seen</a> x 2<br>
Allies :<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(170)">Bounder</a> x 3<br>
Filibert Bolger x 2<br>
<br>
<br>
Shadow (42) <br>
Minions :<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(965)">Goblin Bowman</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(70)">Goblin Marksman</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(972)">Moria Archer Troop</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(73)">Goblin Scavengers</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(72)">Goblin Runner</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(954)">Archer Commander</a> x 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(66)">Goblin Archer</a> x 2<br>
Possessions :<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(75)">Goblin Scimitar</a> x 4<br>
Conditions :<br>
Goblin <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a>y x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(82)">Host of Thousands</a> x 4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(87)">Pinned Down</a> x 2<br>
Goblins Swarms x 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(91)">They Are Coming</a> x 2    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Preliminary Comments : <br>
<br>
1) "Why 42 cards a side ?" you ask.  For a few reasons - <br>
<br>
a) I love the number 42 (the answer to life, the universe and everything - sorry to those youngsters who don&#39;t have the understanding of the significance of the number forty-two)<br>
<br>
b) I like to play LoTR with a bit of variety - more cards means a slightly more unpredictable play.<br>
<br>
c) The shadow side encourages card cycling so I like to have more cards to support this.<br>
<br>
d) I play against some players who like discard decks - more cards means I don&#39;t run out ;-)<br>
<br>
This deck has been played in its current form for some time, and in casual gaming is unbeaten - it does not, however, have a "tournament" record so I have not listed this deck as an "Advanced" deck but I am confident it will do well - I have purpose built variously styled decks including some DeckTech "tournament winner decks" (using proxy cards if I have been short) and had others play those decks against this deck - my deck has not been beaten.  I&#39;ve come close to being beaten, but have still won reaching site 9 with an exhausted and badly poisoned, unaccompanied Frodo.<br>
<br>
2) This is a 1:1 deck - I have played multiplayer with this deck a few times, but I prefer playing against a single opponent.  Please do not review this deck on the basis that it may have multiplayer deficiencies - it is designed purely for 1:1 play.<br>
<br>
3) Companion choice :- I have found the most useful Frodo Adventurer, to reduce twilight cost of all the items Frodo will carry.  I have considered Frodo, Son of Drogo for the Frodo signet and all the hobbit companions with the Frodo signet (allowing other companions to exert to heal Frodo).  Frodo, Old Bilbo&#39;s Heir - his ability to heal allies is not important enough to sacrifice the twilight denial of Adventurer Frodo.<br>
<br>
Sam, Faithful Companion could allow me to play Bill early, but what I gain from Frodo Adventurer outweighs this advantage, and the loss of Sam&#39;s burden removal benefit is potentially fatal.  Sam Proper Poet can be defender + 1, but again I need the burden removal of Faithful Sam.<br>
<br>
Merry, Friend to Sam is fun to play as his power can be added to another companion - but I have found the weapon possession powerup for Merry (Brandywine) is more useful in surviving larger minion hordes.  Merry, Horticulturalist I dont need as I dont play Farmer Maggot.<br>
<br>
Pippin,Intelligence is used to reduce the burden load and then is first to sacrifice if one needs to be.  He has also learned how to effectively use the frying pan !  Pippin, Friend to Frodo was trialled for a while but I found his "tale protection" not as important as his ability to remove 1 burden when he is first played. (yes - he can remove the first burden as you play him into your fellowship at the start of the game)  Pippin, Mr Took has no advantage as I do not play Aragorn or Gandalf.<br>
<br>
4) Why not add other companions ? ... I have made a personal choice to play with a pure hobbit deck, plus I did not want to buy into the potential problems of a large fellowship (there are some very good anti large fellowship cards out there!)<br>
<br>
5) Why not Rare one ring ? ... I have tried both, but with Frodo needing to skirmish I need to keep burden addition under control.<br>
<br>
Basic Strategy Principle : <br>
<br>
Bid high - there is some dependency on being able to control the flow of as many sites as possible, so bid high to win the bid, then force your opponent to play first.  I have deliberately bid low on occassions to test playing first and bid high and chosen to go first (so I have the added problem of carrying burdens) - it is a little more difficult to win before site 9, but the first two sites are designed to support the possibility of having to play first.  <br>
<br>
Site Choices :<br>
<br>
[1] Hobbiton Woods - if I am forced to play first it allows me to play my site 2 which effectively gives me an easy run sites 1-3.<br>
<br>
[2] Buckleberry Ferry - bonus - allows me to avoid skirmish at a time where my hobbits may not be well equipped.<br>
<br>
[3] Frodo&#39;s Bedroom  - starts cycling cards - I get a pickup each time I play an ally.<br>
<br>
[4] Great Chasm - first big support for my Moria swarm.<br>
<br>
[5] The Bridge of Khazad-dum - no choice of course, but I don&#39;t use Balrog - I do better with my normal Moria swarm cards.<br>
<br>
[6] Dimrill Dale - another big booster for my Moria swarm.<br>
<br>
[7] Anduin Confluence - this is a difficult one and really a site chosen by excluding all others as options.  I did, for a while, play with The Great River but I need to access the discard deck for good swarm play.  I can&#39;t afford to play Silverlode banks forcing me to exert all my hobbits, Anduin Wilderland wrecks my minion archery phase, so I am prepared to take the lesser of all the "evils" by discarding allies.  I just try to have the necessary ally (Bounder) in my hand to play after site 7.  If I&#39;m feeling lucky (very lucky!) and my fellowship are all powered up and totally wound free I may make a run from site 5-7 and take what comes with the opponent&#39;s site 7.  This is a nice tactic to use as the opponent is usually ahead on site 6 when I start on site 5 - if I finish on site 7 my opponent is then forced to run 6-8 knowing that I can run 7-9 and win.  A 6-8 opponent run almost always results in overwhelming the fellowship at site 8 (unless I have a bad draw or face a large fellowship).<br>
<br>
[8] Brown Lands - archery anyone?  - the archery boost can destroy large fellowships.  I preferred this to Shores of Nen Hithoel because of the enjoyment of boosting the archery total.  However, if I was playing in tournaments "Shores" would be my first choice as a safeguard against an opponent 7-9 run.<br>
<br>
[9] Summit of Amon Hen - I prefer the draw card per burden option to the 1 extra twilight that other sites give - no other site 9 options support Moria swarm decks as well.<br>
<br>
Fellowship Side Strategy : <br>
<br>
Relies heavily on stealth at sites 2-5.  Once sites 6/7 appear, PATHS and some twilight denial allow hobbit survival to continue and then frying pans in the hands of Sam and Pippin can dispose of a couple of minions that otherwise would overwhelm a hobbit - an exhausted hobbit can be sacrificed at the next site, a dead one can&#39;t !  Frodo and Merry are usually powered up at this stage and can enter the fray as legitimate skirmishers.  The adrenaline rush of having Frodo nearly dead and no companion support at site 9 rocks!  ;-)<br>
<br>
Card commentary :-<br>
Possessions :<br>
Hobbit Sword x 2 - the reliable +2 strength powerup - mostly for Merry.<br>
Frying Pan x 2 - more deadly than the sword - can kill off more powerful minions - for Sam and Pippin if I can get both out.<br>
Mithril Coat x 2 - reduces archery -1, and protects Frodo big time!<br>
Sting x 2 - Frodo&#39;s sword of course, but also use to see opponent&#39;s deck - forewarned is forearmed and you may even get lucky and reduce twilight pool.<br>
Bill the Pony x 2 - who could have an all hobbit fellowship without Bill? (twilight denial).<br>
Events :<br>
Hobbit Stealth x 4 (keeps hobbits alive sites 1 - 5 .. powerup otherwise).<br>
Hobbit Intuition x 4 (keeps hobbits alive sites 1 - 4 ... or powerup).<br>
Power According to His Stature x 4 (keeps Frodo alive, esp. at site 9 when he&#39;s usually alone).<br>
Seek and Hide x 2 (removes damage bonuses).<br>
Conditions :<br>
Nice Imitation x 4 (healing card but don&#39;t have to hold in hand like healing events - no hand clog here).<br>
Fearing the Worst x 2 (some protection against anti-stealth cards and enemy trackers).<br>
O Elbereth! Githoniel! x 2 (Frodo powerup, great protection against Nazgul, removes ring if forced to put ring on).<br>
A Talent for Not Being Seen x 2 (twilight denial).<br>
Allies :<br>
Bounder x 3 (reduces hobbit being overwhelmed).<br>
Filibert Bolger x 2 (helps againts "fierce" skirmishes).<br>
<br>
Shadow Side Strategy: <br>
<br>
Basic archer swarm deck ... play cards as often as possible even if you know they will die in skirmish - the archery phase will hurt your opponent.  By the time sites 7-8 appear, you have a huge chance of overwhelming your opponents (if it hasnt already happened at site 5)<br>
<br>
Card comentary :<br>
Minions :<br>
Goblin Bowman x 4 - basic archer.<br>
Goblin Marksman x 4 - basic archer.<br>
Moria Archer Troop x 4 - power archer - 3 life and extra archery if spots another archer.<br>
Goblin Scavengers x 4 - basic grunt + recycles weapons.<br>
Goblin Runner x 4 - gets two twilight for expending 1 and creating a nuisance minion.<br>
Archer Commander x 2 - archer + strength powerup for all other archers.<br>
Goblin Archer x 2 - archer + ravages opponent&#39;s fellowship archery total.<br>
Possessions :<br>
Goblin Scimitar x 4 - basic weapon but allows card draw when played.<br>
Conditions :<br>
Goblin Armory x 4 - extra twilight when a weapon is played, plus strategic wound prevention.<br>
Host of Thousands x 4 - effectively a minion of your choice (play one from discard).<br>
Pinned Down x 2 - reduces opponent archery total.<br>
Goblins Swarms x 2 - allows recycling minions aside from discard deck.<br>
They are Coming x 2 - allows playing minion from discard deck by discarding 3 cards - allows you to use spare twilight and to remove any "clogged cards".<br>
<br>
Final Comment :<br>
<br>
Potential weaknesses ?<br>
<br>
1) My fellowship is susceptible to an archery shadow side but is in part protected by Mithril Coat and Nice Imitation.  It is reasonably resilient against Uruk and Nazgul, and should survive quite well against non-archer swarm decks.<br>
2) My shadow side is relatively susceptible to large skirmish based fellowships carrying archery protection but it still should be able to dispose of enough companion support to make the opponent think twice about double moving.  Any fellowship side with less than 5 companions is mince meat.  More than 5 is a challenge.<br>
<br>
This is not a tournament deck nor a multiplayer deck - the deck would need to be modified to suit your area&#39;s favoured meta-game.   This deck may need tweaking to provide a bit of multiplayer grunt, but as I am not a multi-player fan I am happy with the way this deck runs for me.  I guess unbeaten in casual games is good.<br>
<br>
Enjoy !     </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=25213"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=25213" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
